Sending keys: ['cat << \'EOF\' > /output/bug_report.txt\nBUG REPORT\n==========\n\nWe identified several major bugs and areas of improvement in the original fraud detection pipeline. Here is a description of each bug, why it is wrong, and how we fixed it:\n\n1. Bug: Data Leakage via StandardScaler\n   - Why it\'s wrong: The pipeline applies standard scaling (`scaler.fit_transform(X)`) to the entire dataset before splitting it into training and validation sets via `train_test_split`. This leaks statistics (mean and variance) from the validation set into the training phase.\n   - How we fixed it: We removed StandardScaler entirely from the pipeline because tree-based models like XGBoost are invariant to monotonic transformations and do not require feature scaling. If scaling were required, we would split the data first, call `.fit_transform()` on the training set, and then call `.transform()` on the validation set.\n\n2. Bug: Standard Scaling of Imputed Sentinel Values (-999)\n   - Why it\'s wrong: The pipeline fills missing values with `-999` before scaling. Scaling transforms the `-999` sentinel to an arbitrary float (e.g., `-12.5`), depending on the distribution of each feature. This distorts feature distributions and ruins the semantic consistency of the sentinel across features, making it harder for the model to use missingness as a cue. Additionally, XGBoost natively handles NaNs far more efficiently than arbitrary constant imputation.\n   - How we fixed it: We kept missing values as `NaN` and let XGBoost natively determine the best split direction for missing data.\n\n3. Bug: Important Categorical Features Completely Dropped\n   - Why it\'s wrong: Categorical columns like `ProductCD`, `card4`, and `card6` were excluded from the model. These variables are highly valuable for identifying fraud patterns.\n   - How we fixed it: We encoded these categorical columns using `LabelEncoder` and kept them in the features list.\n\n4. Bug: Inappropriate Evaluation Metric for Binary Classification\n   - Why it\'s wrong: The `XGBClassifier` was initialized with `eval_metric="rmse"`. Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE) is a regression metric and is inappropriate for evaluating a binary classification model.\n   - How we fixed it: We updated the evaluation metric to `"auc"` (or `"logloss"`), which is suitable for binary classification and matches the validation evaluation metric.\n\n5. Bug: Random Train-Test Split on Temporal/Chronological Data\n   - Why it\'s wrong: Transaction data contains a chronological timestamp (`TransactionDT`). Using a random train-test split causes temporal leakage, where future transaction data is used to train the model to predict past transactions. This results in overly optimistic validation scores and fails to simulate real-world deployment.\n   - How we fixed it: We sorted the transactions chronologically by `TransactionDT` and performed a temporal split, allocating the first 80% for training and the last 20% for validation.\nEOF\n'] min_timeout_sec: 2.0 max_timeout_sec: 180.0
